<head ><name  n='biography' type='ancientGenre'>Biography</name></head>
<p > Biography was not a clearly defined genre in antiquity; there were many authors who wrote works that we could call <soCalled >biographical</soCalled>, and these differ greatly from one another. Some focus on the upbringing of and early influences on historical figures, such as <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Xenophon</name>’s <title >Cyropaedia</title> (<title >The Education of Cyrus</title>) (<bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0032.tlg007:1.1.1' type='cts-urn'>Xen. Cyrop. 1.1.1</bibl>); others focus on political or military exploits, such as <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Arrian</name>'’ <title ><foreign  xml:lang='la'>Anabasis Alexandri</foreign></title> (<title >The Expedition of <name  type='person'>Alexander</name></title>). Biographical sketches can appear in other genres—in <name  n='oratory' type='ancientGenre'>oratory</name>, such as the description of the Athenian general <name  type='person'>Leosthenes</name> in <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Hyperides</name>’ <title >Funeral Oration</title> (<bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0030.tlg006:1' type='cts-urn'>Hyp. 6.1</bibl>), or in works of <name  n='history' type='ancientGenre'>history</name>, such as the descriptions of the Spartan <name  type='person'>Pausanias</name> and the Athenian <name  type='person'>Themistocles</name> in <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Thucydides</name>’ history (see <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0003.tlg001:1.95.1' type='cts-urn'>Thuc. 1.95.1</bibl>; <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0003.tlg001:1.14.3' type='cts-urn'>Thuc. 1.14.3</bibl>; <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0003.tlg001:1.74.1' type='cts-urn'>Thuc. 1.74.1</bibl>). The most extensive surviving body of biographical works is <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Plutarch</name>’s <title >Parallel Lives</title>, biographies of famous Greeks and Romans, which focus on the moral character of their subjects but also provide valuable evidence for political <name  n='history' type='ancientGenre'>history</name>.</p>
<byline >Christopher Blackwell</byline>
